1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,980
Let's plot the relationship between two qualitative variables,

2

00:00:03,980  -->  00:00:07,280
vehicle class and type of vehicle transmission.

3

00:00:07,280  -->  00:00:10,840
To simplify things, I'm only going to look at the main type division,

4

00:00:10,840  -->  00:00:16,400
automatic or manual, which has been stored in the trans_type column.

5

00:00:16,400  -->  00:00:20,660
One way of depicting this could be with a heat map like we saw before.

6

00:00:20,660  -->  00:00:24,960
There's actually a seaborne function for this categorical type of heat map,

7

00:00:24,960  -->  00:00:26,640
the heat map function.

8

00:00:26,640  -->  00:00:29,380
However, this function takes as an argument

9

00:00:29,380  -->  00:00:33,300
a 2D array or data frame with the values to be depicted.

10

00:00:33,300  -->  00:00:35,960
That means that we need to do some summarization

11

00:00:35,960  -->  00:00:38,900
work ourselves before we can create our plot.

12

00:00:38,900  -->  00:00:42,620
First, I use the group by and size functions to get the number of

13

00:00:42,620  -->  00:00:47,540
cars in each combination of the two variables levels as a Panda series.

14

00:00:47,540  -->  00:00:53,160
Then I use reset index to convert the series into a data frame.

15

00:00:53,160  -->  00:00:58,460
Finally, I use Pivot to rearrange the data so that I have vehicle class on rows,

16

00:00:58,460  -->  00:01:02,200
transmission types on columns and values in the cells.

17

00:01:02,200  -->  00:01:04,480
Now we're ready to plot.

18

00:01:04,480  -->  00:01:07,090
This is actually disappointing.

19

00:01:07,090  -->  00:01:09,670
It's actually really hard to compare the counts and

20

00:01:09,670  -->  00:01:12,450
transmission ratios from the colors alone.

21

00:01:12,450  -->  00:01:15,790
You can see that manual is less popular than automatic.

22

00:01:15,790  -->  00:01:18,770
But beyond that, it's hard to tell.

23

00:01:18,770  -->  00:01:22,350
One option we have is to add annotations with counts to the cells,

24

00:01:22,350  -->  00:01:25,630
which makes the representation more tabular in nature.

25

00:01:25,630  -->  00:01:32,370
The FMT parameter set to D ensures that all of the counts are listed as decimal values.

26

00:01:32,370  -->  00:01:34,830
An alternative way of showing the distribution in

27

00:01:34,830  -->  00:01:37,710
counts is through the use of a clustered bar chart.

28

00:01:37,710  -->  00:01:39,950
In the last lesson, you saw how to use

29

00:01:39,950  -->  00:01:44,455
Seaborn's count plot function to generate a bar chart of one variable.

30

00:01:44,455  -->  00:01:47,280
To divide each of the individual bars into

31

00:01:47,280  -->  00:01:49,940
multiple bars for the different transmission types,

32

00:01:49,940  -->  00:01:55,020
we just need to add a huge parameter pointing to the trans_type variable.

33

00:01:55,020  -->  00:01:56,680
With the clustered bar chart,

34

00:01:56,680  -->  00:01:59,220
we can see clearly that many compact cars have

35

00:01:59,220  -->  00:02:02,420
the closest ratio between automatic and manual transmissions,

36

00:02:02,420  -->  00:02:05,980
while large cars have the most distant ratio.
